body:
Maybe flip this around, and explain a bit more how symbol error count works:

```c++
// * Mistakes in a descriptor string are measured in symbol errors. A higher symbol
//   error count is more difficult to detect, because it becomes indistinguishable
//   from a different descriptor.
//   * An error substituting a character from 0123456789()[],'/*abcdefgh@:$%{} for
//     another in that set always counts as 1 symbol error.
//   * A case error always counts as 1 symbol error.
//   * Any other 1 character substitution error counts as 1 or 2 symbol errors.
//   * Note that hex encoded keys are covered by these special characters, whereas xprivs
//     and xpubs use different characters, but already have their own checksum mechanism.
//     Function names like "multi()" use different characters, but mistakes would generally
//     result in an unparseable descriptor. 
```

Some of this is also explained in `DescriptorChecksum` in different wording.

